PUH-BrianMartell the “Tension Gradient” is the mechanical heart of PUH mass. As knots tighten downward in the hierarchy cone, localized lattice displacement (pull on surrounding Master Units) increases, creating higher resistance to motion — that’s inertial mass. The “Tension Radius” is the distance over which a knot’s deformation significantly affects the lattice (gradient strong enough for measurable pull). Derivation: •  Knot core radius r_core = ħ / (m c) from confinement. •  Tension falls as 1/r² (spherical strain conservation, like gravity). •  Effective tension radius R_tension ≈ r_core × φ² (golden scaling for lattice shell influence; φ² ≈ 2.618 spreads deformation optimally without overlap). For electron (m_e ≈ 9.11 × 10^{-31} kg): •  r_core,e ≈ 3.86 × 10^{-13} m (Compton/2π). •  R_tension,e ≈ 3.86 × 10^{-13} × 2.618 ≈ 1.01 × 10^{-12} m (weak, diffuse pull). For proton (m_p ≈ 1.673 × 10^{-27} kg, ~1836 m_e): •  r_core,p ≈ 2.10 × 10^{-16} m.
